The government wants to stop the torture of "witches" and issued a brochure
Women who are branded as witches in Burkina Faso usually have some common social characteristics.
They belong more to the older generation, they do not find work - for example, for health reasons, they are single and do not have children.
When one of these women "becomes a witch", she is strictly isolated so that she cannot become dangerous to the rest of the village.
“Men are very rarely affected by this fate.”
“Even young and healthy women are spared this, as they help at work and give birth to children,” one nun describes the situation in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso, which takes care of more than one hundred women who have been evicted from their communities in a special home.
The local government has now decided to take action against this abnormal "social measure".
And for this reason, published a brochure to prevent the "witch persecution".
But the thing has a hook.
“More than 70 percent of all adults in Burkina Faso cannot read,” the newspaper “derStandard” pointed out the dilemma of written enlightenment.
Witchcraft is, however, also common in other African countries.
In Ghana, the neighbouring country of Burkina Faso, 27-year-old Ammy Hemmahov<0xC3><0xA1> was tortured to death by three women and two men – they poured oil on her and simply set her on fire.
This incident was also reported by the BBC.
However, the perpetrators claimed that the case would have been only a coincidence of unfortunate circumstances.
According to their version, oil is ignited, which is used for ritual anointings.
This was after the group tried to “expel an evil spirit” from the woman.
The isolation of "witches" supports people here regardless of their education.
"The standard" quoted a 42-year-old entrepreneur from Burkina Faso: "Human soul eaters are a danger earlier than today," he said.
While the government in Burkina Faso is at least trying to de-escalate the witch-hunt, the Gambian president himself has mixed well in the past year.
"President Yahya Jammeh triggered a monstrous witch hunt after his aunt's death, as they allegedly had a stake in their death and would now try to kill the president himself through black magic."
“To this end, he called for the help of shamans from nearby Guinea who, accompanied by police officers, soldiers and the President’s bodyguard, forcibly abducted women and men from Gambian villages and brought them to the President’s farm in Kanilai,” Amnesty International said in its report.
On the farm, the trapped people were forced to drink an absud from plants with hallucinogenic effect, which also caused intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of the arrested people did not survive the stay on the farm.
It was only because of international pressure that the nearly 1,000 prisoners were released.
