A longer index finger than a ring finger means a lower risk of getting cancer
Men whose index finger is longer than the ring finger are obviously at a lower risk of developing prostate cancer.
This is the surprising result of a study published Wednesday in the British Journal of Cancer.
This is said to be related to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our results show that the relative length of the fingers can serve as a simple test for prostate cancer risk, particularly in men up to sixty," said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the University of Warwick Cancer Research Institute.
The finger could thus help determine which men should necessarily undergo a prostate cancer test, especially if there are genetic risks or other risk factors, such as family health burdens, Ms. Eeles added.
Between 1994 and 2009, she and her colleagues in the UK tracked more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer, but also 3,000 healthy men.
In more than half of the study participants, the index finger of the right hand was shorter than the ring finger.
These men had the same chance of prostate cancer as 19 percent of those men whose ring and index fingers were the same length.
In men whose index finger was longer than the ring finger, however, this risk decreased by 33 percent, in men up to sixty even by 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers mentioned, which are already formed in prenatal age, obviously reflects the different levels of sex hormones to which the child was exposed in the womb.
Less testosterone is equivalent to a longer index finger.
Previous research has shown that testosterone accelerates the growth of prostate cancer.
V<0xC3><0xA1>clav Pa<0xC4><0x8D>es, a leading Czech geneticist and former chair of the Academy of Sciences, told <0xC4><0x8C>TK that he was familiar with this study but did not consider the relationship between finger length and cancer risk to be “completely proven”.
