The first step in manufacturing seems simple.
Luciano dumps the basic ingredients of milk, cream, milk powder, sugar and stabilizers into a large mixer that heats everything to 85 degrees with an electronic program and then immediately cools to four degrees.
Then he turns a cock on the machine, and out comes a pasteurized white base cream, the basis for all types of milk ice cream.
Immediately the teacher is stormed with questions: Can ice cream be made only with natural substances without a stabilizer?
How can one let go of one’s own desire to experiment?
Luciano warns against being led astray by the zeitgeist.
Anyone who talks about ice cream "only from natural ingredients" may still have used stabilizers - usually a natural product, such as guar kernel flour from guar bean.
