To these results came the Latinobar<0xC3><0xB3>metro survey, conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively in The Economist.
This survey has been conducted regularly since 1995 and shows the change of opinion in this region.
Two facts are particularly striking in this year's survey of September and October.
First, the good mood in Latin America
and secondly, the growing interest in democracy and its main institutions.
In many countries on the South American Pacific coast, the democratic movement has increased sharply (see Table 1).
In Peru, for example, where the economy has grown by about 6% annually since 2002, the number of pro-democracy advocates rose from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
Even in Mexico, where the economy has been recovering since last year’s strong downturn, such a trend can be seen.
However, only half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the most populous countries in the region, are convinced Democrats, which lowers the regional average (see Figure 2).
Approximately 44% of respondents said that they were satisfied with their country's democratic practice, which is as many as last year, but 25% more than in 2001 (Figure 3).
About 34% trust the Congress of their country and 45% of their government. Both values correspond to those of last year, but show a significant increase compared to 2003 (17% and 24%).
A decade ago, Latin America’s economic crises undermined efforts for more democracy.
This continued even during the global economic crisis, perhaps because the countries of Latin America experienced only a short recession and quickly recovered.
In addition, the poor were captured by a stronger social network.
(According to reports by the UN Economic Commission for Latin America from this week, the poverty rate in Latin America rose only slightly in 2009 and fell again this year by 32%.)
However, from country to country, there are strong mood differences (see Figure 4).
Brazil’s strong economy and the popularity of outgoing President Luiz In<0xC3><0xA1>cio Lula da Silva are reflected in a widespread thinking of progress.
In Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more noticeable and violent crimes have increased, this is less the case.
For the second time since the survey began, many respondents in Latin America see crime in their country as a bigger problem than unemployment (see Figure 5).
About 31% say that either they or a family member were the victims of a crime in the last year, but compared to 38% last year, the values have fallen and thus reach the lowest level since 1995.
The increasing economic performance is reflected in the stronger support for the private and market economy: about 71% of respondents across the region indicated that the private sector is essential for development, in 2007 it was 56% (see Figure 6).
About 58% stated that only the market economy can bring progress to their country, compared to 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela have maintained this view (and 80% are for a private sector), even though their left-wing president, Hugo Ch<0xC3><0xA1>vez, has nationalized many private companies.
According to 19% of respondents (18% last year), Brazil has the highest weight in the region, followed by the United States (9%, unchanged since last year) and Venezuela (9% compared to 11% last year).
In contrast, respondents in Mexico and most Central American countries see the United States as the most influential country, with Venezuela taking over this role in the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
