Police operations in China are getting softer
As a training officer, Tang Shenbin stepped over an urban square, checking his nervous subordinates and issuing orders with military authority and muted voice.
He wanted his female members of Chengguan – China’s robust guardians of the urban order, feared and despised for their arbitrary raids and their penchant for violence – to impress the audience.
"Stand straight!"
"Look straight!"
"Show them," he whispered to them, "how pretty girls they are!"
Four girls, barely out of the teenage age, with white gloves and identical olive green jackets and pants stood tight.
Four pairs of black pumps stood in a straight line.
Four neat hats sat perfectly on the hair held with blue and white stripes.
“They look average to me,” Mr. Tang remarks disparagingly.
"Models are beautiful."
Several governments have already tried to polish up the image of China’s city inspectors.
In a city, all new applicants must have a university degree.
The province of Guangdong introduced a bright blue uniform instead of the gray-green one.
Wuhan in central China replaced violence with low-lights: According to reports, in 2009, 50 officials circled around an improperly positioned snack cart and stared at the operator until he packed up after half an hour and left the square.
Xindu, a city district in Chengdu with 680,000 inhabitants, wants to fundamentally change the image.
Since 2003, 13 women have been reinforcing the urban police lines. They have been selected special because of their appearance, their good figure and their youth.
They are supposed to give the brutal police a softer, feminine aspect.
But unfortunately, Scarlett Johansson would hardly be able to improve the bad image that the Chinese have of these city commands.
That's right, the critics.
Unlike the police, these officials are only allowed to enforce city laws by means of fines or other administrative penalties.
But the Chinese media routinely show a different picture.
In January 2008, officials in Hubei province beat a bystander to death when he filmed them using his mobile phone as they staged a protest against a garbage dump.
Last year, a training manual of Beijing officials was stolen and published on the Internet, describing how criminals can be beaten without bloodshed.
This year, a Shanghai watermelon dealer suffered brain injuries after a handshake with five officials.
A violent video game that can be downloaded from the Internet shows officials trained in China in an attack on street vendors.
“Chengguan is scaring the government,” the national newspaper China Daily lamented last year, after further controversy over the tactics.
The newspaper called for a "really thorough clean-up".
Skeptics find the current approach to be clearly inadequate.
When the district searched for eight female recruits by ad in October, an editorial in the Beijing Evening News asked whether the women had real tasks or should only serve as visual distractions.
Probably both.
According to the job advertisement, women aged 18 to 22 with good figure and "harmonic facial features" were sought.
They should be above average - over 1.5m or 5 feet, 2 1/2 inches.
The employment relationship ends when you reach the age of 26.
According to the officials, the activity is too strenuous for women over 25.
"The most important thing is their image," an unnamed district official told quasi-government website Rednet.com.
"Whether the candidates get the job depends first on their external appearance, such as size, weight, facial features, etc."
Then comes temperament and "inner qualities".
“Female Chengguans are like flower vases,” he said, adding, “but beyond that, they have other duties.”
Zheng Lihua, deputy head of the district's city administration, would not like to add to this description,
However, China admitted that size specifications in job ads are not uncommon for both genders.
The same applies to uniform facial features.
Whether this is the same as good looks is controversial in China.
But people with disabilities or physical disabilities do not need to apply.
"Unfortunately, we can't use lames or buckligens here," said Mr. Zheng.
"Your image would not be good."
Liu Yi, who patrols on Baoguang Square near a monastery, is 22, has apple pies and a well-shaped mouth.
She didn’t feel sexist, so much emphasis is placed on her appearance.
"Do you think I look sexy in this uniform?" she asks with an ironic look.
Her colleague with the dimples, 21-year-old Xu Yang, comments, "We have the task of representing the image of the city."
According to their information, they do not regret the short-term hiring, as they have more ambitious career plans than simply scaring traders through the streets to prevent them from doing business.
Every morning, the strip deals with about twelve street vendors who try to sell as many rolls and tofu dishes as possible on foot or by bike before they are chased away.
"Mr. Wang, please get out of here."
"We have told you this so many times!" explains Frl. Xu to a merchant who had fled on foot and had temporarily abandoned his pasta kitchen attached to a bicycle cart.
According to the officials, the activity is more monotonous than exhausting.
“It’s almost the same every day,” explains Huang Jing, 20, who studies in leisure sales.
"All routine."
One reason for this is that the female officials are not allowed to confiscate the goods of the dealers, like their male colleagues.
They can only threaten criminals by reporting them to their male superiors.
This is to protect them from public hostility, to which officials in China are often exposed.
This year, hundreds of residents of Kunming, the capital of Yunnan province, raided after the rumor circulated that Chengguan officials had killed a dealer.
More than a dozen police and Chenguan officials were injured in the nighttime incident, 14 government vehicles were overturned or set on fire.
Xindu has so far been spared such violent outbursts.
But unrest cannot be ruled out.
Just two blocks from the quiet Baonguang Square, where the female officers patrolled that morning, more than 50 people gathered at a street corner.
Officials had confiscated a motorcycle, which was repaired in a workshop instead of on the sidewalk, contrary to the regulations.
The owner screamed Zeter and Mordio.
After 15 minutes of hesitation, the officials made their way to their vehicles with a grim face and continued with the motorcycle and its owner.
Li Xuedong, 40, a male stripe coordinator, stayed behind, turning his white name tag around to remain anonymous.
Like their colleagues, the coordinators – men over 40 – play a purely supportive role.
But they were not trained to present a clean image.
“Sometimes we talk verbally.”
"Sometimes physically as well," explains Mr. Li soberly.
“Most of the time, people start fighting.”
