Can politeness connect the separating?
After a campaign of defamation and negativity, little courtesy has broken out in Washington this week.
Is it the omen of a real two-party cooperation or a moment of illusion before one quickly returns to the struggle of the parties in the capital?
Tuesday’s meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders did not break through the big questions that had to be addressed during the so-called “lame duck session,” the session at the end of a government period in which decisions are no longer made.
After all you hear, it was neither a polite discussion between two different sides nor a consideration of their shared responsibility to govern, but rather an empty episode of a partial point-gathering.
The president’s public meeting of the deficit commission on Wednesday was also civilised, despite the political differences that continue to exist between members.
It seems clear that a close interaction over a period of months creates mutual respect, obfuscating the ideological divide that continues to separate members from one another.
This is hardly enough to claim that a new era of cooperation has begun.
Both sides are now in a testing phase - one requiring the other to show willingness to cooperate and compromise, while trying to weigh the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters after a renewed party war.
Therefore, the meeting on Tuesday itself and its assessment by the participants were limited to a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too great and too deep to expect a rapid change in the atmosphere that has prevailed over the past two years.
Whether it’s taxes, donations, health or expectations, the two sides are miles apart.
Last but not least, Washington’s November election has been mild for at least a short time.
“No question, the tone has changed,” said Pete Wehner, an official with the Bush administration who now works for the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
“This is inevitable after the election.
Elections rekindle partial passions that die out again.
And that's a good thing."
In some issues, especially those on the “lame duck session” agenda, Republicans and Democrats have little choice but to find a solution.
Bush’s tax cuts end at the end of the year, and no one supports that.
Both sides want to find a way to get some or all of them, whether temporary or permanent.
Similarly, a compromise on increased unemployment benefits is to be expected, if only because the Republicans cannot afford to believe that the favored tax cuts for the rich while denying support to unemployed workers.
After Tuesday’s meeting at the White House, optimism has risen that these issues can be agreed during the “lame duck session” and at the same time the New START Treaty can be ratified.
But William Glaston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful co-operation on pressing issues of the lame duck session "does not necessarily lead to permanent co-operation of the parties when the new 112th Congress is convened in January.
Instead, he says, a phase of disagreement is more likely, perhaps even inevitable.
“After the things that need to be done are done, this short-term psychology will turn into confrontation,” he said.
Wehner is also skeptical – and this skepticism is shared by many – courtesy leads to true cooperation.
"I see a lot of what's happening from today to 2012 as pre-fight, or shadow boxes, for the main event of 2012," he said.
The reasons for this have a lot to do with the emergence of the new Republican majority in the White House and with the tea party voters who served their education.
As worried as Republican leaders may be about playing too high a poker, they know they must try to keep their promises to cut government spending and put health care reform out of action.
These party lines are already evident in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the Deficit Commission, which include tax reform and the raising of some taxes, as well as the raising of the retirement age and the lowering of state spending.
Vice Presidents Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, in their own estimation, have pushed so hard to put the deficit issue on the public agenda that it can no longer be ignored.
But they need 14 of the 18 votes within the Commission to make their plan an official recommendation and they are fighting hard to get even close to that number.
The greatest resistance can be found in the elected representatives of the body, since in financial matters, at least today, there is little room for manoeuvre or little sympathy for compromises.
Galston predicts two phases in the fight between the White House and the Republicans in Congress.
The first fight will take place next year in the form of party clashes, when Republicans challenge Obama regarding the state budget, taxes and health care system, later followed by a phase of greater two-party cooperation.
What will lead to this change?
Public opinion.
It is proven that, despite the partisanship of the current election, the majority of Americans still want the two parties to work together.
If confrontation leads to a dead end, as happened in 1995, then both parties must pay careful attention to the public reaction.
Whoever is condemned to lose will have to change course and seek compromise.
This may in fact be an optimistic view.
Party bias and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s, and they seem to be a larger ideological divide between Obama and Congressional Republicans than they were between President Bill Clinton and Republicans at the time.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a far more consequential 2012 election.
In this regard, the courtesy shown this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on both sides to find a common denominator in the issues that the two continue to separate.
