“The direct connection of the Moscow government to crime has led some to call it ‘disrupted’ and to conclude that the government is acting more like a kleptocracy than a government,” the memo said.
“Criminal elements enjoy a ‘kryshna’ (a term from the world of criminals/the mafia, which literally means ‘roof’ or protection) that extends across the police, state security (FSB), the service supervisory authority (MVD) and the prosecutor’s office as well as through the entire Moscow government bureaucracy.
Experts have discovered a three-layered structure within the criminal world of Moscow.
"Luzhkov is in the top spot."
"FSB, MVD and the militia are in the second stage."
"Lastly, the ordinary criminals and the criminal inspectors follow at the lowest level."
"This is an incompetent system in which criminal groups in some areas close a gap because the city does not offer any help."
The report goes on to say that the FSB is cashing money from the biggest companies and that the police are arresting small businessmen.
One source, it is said, "explained that Moscow's business owners understand that it is best to get protection from the MVD and FSB (and not from organized crime) because they not only have more weapons, resources and power than the criminals, but also because they are protected by law."
"For this reason, protection by criminal gangs is no longer as demanded as before."
The memo notes that while the collection of funds is extensive, the protection itself is not very modest; even those who pay are sometimes arrested.
Those who do not pay, find their business closed very quickly - due to one or another pretext.
Medvedev has spoken several times about fighting corruption, but at the same time has noted that he has made little progress.
The memo of the embassy contains descriptions of men carrying suitcases that were probably full of money going to the Kremlin.
"In his fight against corruption, Medvedev has to rely on the bureaucrats," Georgi Satarov, director of Indem, a Moscow-based commission of experts, said in a recent interview.
"But he's part of that bureaucracy."
“It is not part of the political class because a political class in Russia no longer exists.”
Without politicians, without an opposition, without a separation of powers, he says, corruption is inevitable.
Across the country, he estimates, corruption costs Russia more than $300 billion a year.
The country ranks 154th in a recent survey of the global perception of corruption by the non-governmental organization Transparency International (countries are listed from “least corrupt” to “most corrupt”).
The disclosure of the memo of the American embassy, which took place late in the evening after Moscow time, will surely provoke resentment within the Russian government, although, since Luzhkov can be accused of Moscow’s mistakes, it can also be a possibility for the Kremlin to claim that they solve the problems.
In an interview with Larry King for CNN, Putin claimed that the WikiLeaks documents could be a forgery and reacted angrily to the revelation that American diplomats called him Batman and Medvedev Robin.
“The truth is that it’s about our interaction, which is an important factor in domestic politics in this country,” he said.
“But to be honest, we wouldn’t have expected this to happen with such arrogance, with such pressure and in such an unethical way, you know.”
