It is assumed that Merkel’s position is not a fault of her public relations work.
On the contrary, it is a new round in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
In doing so, Germany takes a fundamentally new perspective on shaping our future, which conflicts with the maintenance of the ancient traditions of a large part of its partners.
In view of the resistance in Europe, Germany is beginning to speculate on three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first: A strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the south would have to leave the euro area.
The second: the reintroduction of the Deutsche Mark – although this sounds more like science fiction at the moment – is supported by a large majority of public opinion, about 50 percent of the population.
The third: a reshaping of the euro according to German proposals, which means: more macroeconomic control; strict budgetary management; punishing countries that fail to comply; possibly suspending some countries' payments and extending the costs of potential adjustment measures to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been for some time, so there are no excuses now.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission created incentives for deficits and the German government pulled out a constitutional reform to prevent this from 2016 onwards.
This was the first sign of the drift between what Germany considered necessary (strict tax plans and stable public finances) and the practices of its European partners, including France.
The second sign set the Central European country, when Merkel painfully postponed the decision to save Greece.
At the time, this was strongly criticized, but the fact is that the political consensus in Germany, the public and the published opinion were absolutely against a rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel has come out with a clear position, calling for a reform of the agreements of the European Union to allow the rescue of a country while obliging private lenders to bear some of the costs.
This position was interpreted as anti-European, as it pushed forward the Irish crisis and all of the following.
But their proposal, although somewhat sweetened, has been adopted, and in the coming months we will be taking part in the reform of the European Union, which is supposed to make these measures possible from 2013 onwards.
Germany has drawn a red line, which it does not intend to cross.
It tells everyone that - even if unpopular measures have to be taken now - from this date the old functioning of the euro will no longer exist.
2013 will be the year of the birth of a new currency area, in which the opposing countries can be severely punished, forced to declare themselves insolvent, and in this case the private sector must bear some of the costs.
Germany shows us that we need to take a hard growth path, with high savings and investment rates, moderation of consumption, improvement of productivity and competitiveness, as well as positive foreign trade balances.
The other alternative, which is based on debt and construction with huge holes in the balance of payments, as it was cited by Spain during boom times, will simply not be accepted.
The offer is clear.
And we would do badly not to understand it.
It is not just about reducing the state deficit to three percent by 2013.
The demands are much harder.
And the worst thing we could do under these conditions is cheat ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will be more calm.
And that we will take advantage of the opportunities offered to us by spring 2013.
Zapatero seems to have understood this as well, and his double announcement (the promised reforms after meeting with the big companies last Saturday and the announcement of new measures yesterday) indicates that despite criticism of Merkel, the hypothesis of creating order in her own home has prepared its way.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there, and it doesn’t look like anything would change.
Among the options that have been considered is the fact that we would have to leave the euro area, which is full of unserious countries.
In this case, Germany could still tell us that it warned us.
Sport and the Rule of Circumvention
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against Ajax show inventiveness, but not the will to circumvent a sanction.
The alleged exclusion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the November 23 game against Ajax in the Champions League led to a lot of ink being poured on whether or not it was an unsportsmanlike act and whether or not both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is commonly known, the two players lost time a few minutes before the end of the game (their team had clearly already won) and played several fouls so that the referee showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid would lead its group, the two players will meet the prescribed penalty in the next league game against Auxerre and thus enter the next game phase without cards.
Finally, the UEFA disciplinary committee punished the club's coach, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card under such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is more often found in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos – the unwritten but in this sport followed rules.
Part of the debate surrounding the case is due to the fact that a team of Real Madrid football club (who, in his anthem, professed nobility and honor and on other occasions had punished its players for similar incidents) played the main role, and to the dramatization by Mourinho, who added an episode more pros and cons to his long history than theatral.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this behaviour, which is not expressly prohibited by the statutes, is contrary to the principles of sport, that is, whether these actions constitute a circumvention of the rules. In fact, this approach adheres to the statutes of sport, but seems to circumvent its meaning.
In this case, the damage caused to the sports spirit should be investigated.
The sports spirit defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not compromised by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to prevent the opposing players from taking undue advantage of the opposing team, which did not happen either.
The paradox of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not correspond to what we usually mean by false play or circumvention of rules, because the circumvention of the rule was not carried out secretly to avoid a sanction, but it should be as conspicuous as possible so that it is punished by the referee.
The players waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is, what kind of advantage did the adversaries draw from the deliberate fouls.
It should be emphasized here that the rival was not put in a more unfavorable position nor advantages were gained for the game played, because the obvious result of this action was that the own team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because then the club does not have these players.
The obvious advantage is that players start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But this is a long-term, to a certain degree uncertain advantage, as the team could eventually also quit. In addition, with this procedure, players receive a sanction and move to the second card cycle, in which they quit with one card less than in the first cycle due to card accumulation.
It is therefore not so clear whether this is really an advantage.
Ultimately, such practices are not directed against the spirit of sport, which also includes strategic decisions in order to derive the greatest possible benefit from the regulations.
In this case, the players did not want to bypass the sanction (this would actually be a clear case of rule-breaking), they wanted to choose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding punishment or escaping from it.
Although the boundary between the inventive step and the control environment is blurred, I believe that this case is a clear case of inventive step.
I have the impression that the controversy arose as a result of two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the nature of the provoked rule transmission.
The damage done to the principles of sport by these actions is less ethical than rather aesthetic in nature.
