China maintains its goals to reduce greenhouse gases
The representative of China said at COP16 that his country had made enormous efforts to reduce carbon footprints and it would maintain its offer to cut 40 to 45 percent of its greenhouse gas emissions by 2020.
China is keeping its offer to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, according to Su Wei, the country’s representative at COP16.
At his first public appearance at the 16th United Nations World Climate Summit (COP16), Su Wei assured that his country had made enormous efforts to reduce carbon footprints and transform its industry.
He said his country had invested $245 million over the past four years to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
However, he said China would not change its goals, but would work with the international community on the matter.
He explained that China’s climate change strategy is divided into four aspects: dialogue, capacity building, institution building, and support for pilot programs.
In all aspects, progress has been made, including the adoption of a new energy law last year that includes targets for reducing gas emissions, he said.
On the other hand, he stressed that in China, the authorities of the states had cooperated with those of the central state and the municipalities in order to achieve the goals of energy saving, effective use of energy and reduction of emissions.
In addition, he said, several multi-year plans have already been launched or completed, both those funded by the Chinese government and those that received funds from other countries.
For example, he referred to the Energy Efficiency Programme, which had been implemented over the past five years and had received investments from the United Nations (UN), the government and from private hands.
There is also a project at the provincial level on climate change, another on the exchange of traditional light bulbs through energy-saving bulbs and another on mitigation and adaptation, he explained.
Martin Krol, the country’s government’s climate change science adviser, confirmed that China’s efforts are far greater than would be commonly believed.
He pointed out that per capita emissions of greenhouse gases in China are six tons per person, while in the United States it is 100 tons. China is responsible for a 9% total contribution to environmental pollution.
It is also making unprecedented progress in the field of energy use. Energy efficiency has been increased by twenty percent in the last five years and another one is expected to happen by 2020, he explained.
