The U.S. changes the rules for obtaining a visa
The persons must present themselves before their conversation at the consulate at the service points for the visa application; costs will be reduced by waiting times.
As of January 10, 2011, the procedures for applying for a visa will change at the Embassy of the United States and at the Consulates.
In the new procedure, most applicants have to present their initial letters in English to the visa application service (ASC) before they are interviewed at the consulate.
The staff of the ASC shall record the biometric data of the applicant, which will be checked by the consulate before the interview.
The new procedure has certain advantages for the aspirants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa is reduced, because it is no longer necessary to pay the appointment agreement, the processing of the visa application and the transport service with which the document is handed over separately.
The applicant shall only make a single payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas with application (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for hands and investors.
Those who only want to extend their visa do not need to have a conversation at the consulate, they only need to introduce themselves at the nearest ASC, where they will be presented with their documents and their fingerprints taken.
Since the biometric data are collected in the ASC, applicants who need a second appointment for the interview at the consulate will remain there for less time than before.
Those applying for the visa in the consulates of Ciudad Ju<0xC3><0xA1>rez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer have to pay the service charge of $26.
Further information on the new visa application procedure can be found at the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
NASA Announces Discovery of Extraterrestrial Life
The North American Space Agency called a press conference to present a finding tomorrow that will have an impact on the search for living things in space.
The National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) of the United States announced tomorrow, Thursday, an astrobiological discovery that could confirm the theory of the existence of extraterrestrial life.
The finding will be presented tomorrow at a press conference at NASA headquarters in Washington by experts in astrobiology, a science that studies the origin, development, distribution and future of life in the universe.
At the press conference, NASA assured that it would present “a supervisory finding for the search for extraterrestrial life,” triggering speculation among experts from other countries.
The discovery could prove the theory that, in hostile environments previously considered uninhabitable, human-like creatures could exist; it has been hypothesized that they could transform into intelligent living beings - just like humans - if their living conditions improved.
It appears to be a microbe found at the bottom of Mono Lake in Yosemite National Park, California, living in an environment considered too toxic for all conceivable life forms, as the lake is heavily arsenic-containing.
In some ways, the microbe is using arsenic as a survival resource, and considering this ability, the chances are that there could be similar life on other planets that don’t have our protective atmosphere.
When these organisms metabolize arsenic, according to astrobiologists, it has been proven that "there is actually a different life form, a second life form that is different from the one we know."
The space agency will announce tomorrow, on Thursday, at the press conference the actual scope of its fund.
The conference is attended by geobiologist Pamela Conrad, who is studying the possibility of life on Mars, and biologist Steven Benner, one of the scientists who studied Titan (the largest moon of Saturn) under the question of whether its chemical composition resembles that of Earth.
