Global plan for the renewal of lighting
The United Nations has proposed in Cancun a plan to renew the lighting of households, trade and industry in 100 countries with a view to achieving a reduction in greenhouse gas (GHG) equivalent to almost one-third of the additional reduction that needs to be implemented to stabilize the Earth's climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan takes its position in the steps of the concrete major projects that the UN hopes to implement in Cancun to compensate for the absence of mandatory reduction commitments of developed countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, the main problem would be avoided in the form of 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of the FCKW emitted to the earth due to lighting, if the white glowing pears, which so far still represent a monopoly of 50 to 70% on the market, would be replaced by fluorescent or better yet, by light-emitting diodes (LEDs).
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This corresponds to an equivalent of 70% of the emissions of the global fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, the major emitters such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, had committed to voluntary reduction plans to reduce global FFC emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, 5 Gt would have to be subtracted from this balance in order to stabilize the climate increase by 2 degrees Celsius from today until 2020 in order to prevent it from getting out of control.
In the white glowing pears, 95% of the energy escapes in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% produce light.
With the compact fluorescent bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75%, with the new LED bulbs, this energy requirement is reduced by twice.
On average, the compact fluorescent bulbs last between 6,000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED light bulbs, such as those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week - by the way, this company has participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a white-hot bulb, which should be used to indicate the savings opportunities of the exchange plan, which is modified in 100 countries.
In addition to the fact that completely novel incandescent bulbs emit very little heat, they can also work with a control resistor.
And they do not contain any mercury.
Several specialists have shown that compact fluorescent bulbs have reserves because they contain mercury and that it is therefore necessary to dispose of them as special waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless the producers provide a place of acceptance.
However, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet, according to the report, is not the compact fluorescent bulb, but rather the coal-fired power plants that emit significantly more mercury to generate the electricity wasted by the white-hot bulbs.
In the United States alone, these coal-fired power plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury annually.
The report details the gains that each country would make thanks to this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save one billion dollars a year in the purchase of electricity and eight million tons of CO2, which is the equivalent of 3.5 coal-fired power plants, the construction of which would cost Indonesia 2.5 billion.
