Vengeful hackers and empathetic spies
The WikiLeaks affair has a double meaning.
On the one hand, it has turned out to be an obvious scandal, a scandal that is merely a scandal in the sense of hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes at the international level, and gives a foretaste of the future dominated by regression.
But let's proceed in turn.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every file created by a secret service (of any nation) is composed exclusively of newspaper clippings.
The “extraordinary” American revelations about Berlusconi’s sexual habits throw nothing away beyond what you’ve been getting to read in every x-journal for months anyway (except those whose owner is Berlusconi), and the horrifyingly caricatured profile Gaddafi has since offered cabaret artists.
The rule that the secret files can only consist of known news is essential for the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
If you go to a library dedicated to esoteric publications, you will realize that every work (about the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Chateau, the Templars or the Rosicrucians) repeats exactly what has already been written in previous works.
This is not only because the author of occult texts does not want to publish research (yet because he did not know where to find news about the non-existent), but because those who devote themselves to occultism believe in nothing but what they already know and confirm what they have already learned.
This is also the success mechanism of Dan Brown.
As well as the secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or limited mind) is also the head of the secret service (otherwise he could be anything, for example, editor at Libération), who only considers what he acknowledges to be true.
The top-secret information about Berlusconi that the American embassy in Rome had sent to the State Department was the same as those that Newsweek had published the week before.
So why was such a lifting of the disclosures of these dossiers made?
On the one hand, they say what every educated person already knows, namely that the embassies - at least since the end of the Second World War and since then also the heads of government can call each other or take a plane to meet for dinner - have lost their diplomatic function and have turned, with the exception of some small representational tasks, into spying.
Any viewers of investigative films know this very well, and it is not out of hypocrisy that you do so to ignore it.
Nevertheless, the fact of repeating it publicly violates the task of hypocrisy and serves to put American diplomacy in a bad light.
Second, the idea that an x-any hacker can tap into the secrets of the most powerful country in the world carries the significant blow against the prestige of the State Department.
In addition, the scandal brings less victims, than rather the "sharffrichter" in distress.
But let us devote ourselves to the profound nature of what has happened.
Formerly, in Orwell’s time, all power could be bundled together like a big brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell’s prophecy could have turned out to be perfectly correct since then, where you could control every movement thanks to the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway chosen and so on; the citizen would become the total victim of the eye of power.
But if you look at what is going on today, that even the secret crypts of power can no longer escape the control of a hacker, then the control process ceases to be one-sided and becomes circular.
The power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - elected as the citizen's avenger - can expose the secrets of power.
But how can a power that is no longer able to keep its own secrets hold?
True, Georg Simmel already said that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed to Clinton); it is also true that any knowledge of Berlusconi’s or Merkel’s character is basically a secret free of secret, since it reveals the public sphere, but in the style of Wikiak, I have to admit that the secret is to be open to the public.
WikiLeaks has done neither Sarkozy nor Merkel wrong, but Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this outrage inflicted on such a mighty power?
It is obvious that the states will no longer put any reserved information online in the future - this would be like a sticker on the street corner.
But it is equally obvious that it is in vain with the current technologies to hope to be able to keep confidential reports over the phone secret.
Nothing is easier than to find out if and when a head of state moved in an airplane and contacted one of his colleagues.
In the future, how can private and ear-only relationships be maintained?
I know very well that my prediction at the moment sounds science fiction and novel, but I see myself compelled to imagine government agents secretly moving empathetically on uncontrollable routes, carrying their messages nowhere but in mere memory, and beyond, carrying little information with them.
The information would be stored in locked drawers in a single copy: basically, Watergate’s spying attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks’.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is moving forward like a cancer these days, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph had revolutionized communication, the Internet is reconstructing a telegraph with (telephone) wire.
The (analogous) video cassettes had allowed the film researchers to explore a film band by band, by winding from the back to the front and venting all the secrets of the assembly, while today the (numerical) CDs allow nothing but to jump from chapter to chapter, i.e. in macro portions.
The high-speed trains take you from Rome to Milan within three hours, while this requires three and a half hours by plane, including the changeover.
It is therefore not unusual for politics and communication technology to return to car and horse.
One last observation.
In earlier times, the press tried to understand what secrets were forged between the embassies.
At present, it is the embassies that demand confidential information from the press.
Climate: how France is making good on its financial promises
One year after the Copenhagen Treaty, it is time to examine compliance with the fast-paced funding promises (also called "Fast Start" or early funding) implemented by developing countries.
And already the rough French shipping companies have been uncovered.
Under the Copenhagen Treaty, developing countries committed to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The EU has pledged 7.2 billion euros over three years, France 1.26 billion euros (i.e. 420 million per year).
On the occasion of the opening of COP16, the EU drew up all the registers to convince its partners of the fact of its commitment to fast-start funding: detailed progress report of its Member States, press conference, major side events, distribution of brochures.
Operation Transparency is remarkable and highly valued for its actual value: developing countries and civil society like to see it when all developed countries do the same at the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2.2 billion in 2010, setting it on track to meet its commitment of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look at the details, things are a little more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Treaty, this money should be “new and additional” to ensure that an additional bet has been made without harming public development aid.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what "new and additional" means.
While the EU Commission had proposed harmonisation, certain Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the guideline that he considers to be the best.
For example, the EU Commission has chosen as a benchmark for those of 2009: international financing is maintained, and gives 150 million over three years as part of the financing "Fast-Start".
Other countries have chosen similar benchmarks, either in terms of year or in terms of conditions at the level of public development aid.
In return, France felt that the funding for "all new projects" of 2010 was "new and additional".
In other words, there are no benchmarks for spending in the previous year or at the global level of public development aid.
In concrete terms, the total amount of French support to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease) - France pretends to comply with its commitment to "new and additional" financing.
Another crucial element is the breakdown into donations and loans.
There is no rule on this, and everyone chooses their calculation mode.
Some, such as France, find 1 borrowed <0xE2><0x82><0xAC> as equivalent to 1 donated <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>.
Obviously, this is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans for certain profitable investments (often projects linked to emission control, which are based on the most effective technology) can be justified, it is misleading to present the euro, which is taken as an equivalent for a donated euro... In addition, only the cost of the loan for the donor country should be considered as an asset.
But France has nothing in mind other than the following consideration: it “respects” its commitment of 420 million euros by taking 91.5% loans (389.8 million euros) and donating 8.5% (36.1 million euros) – see also the EU document to convince itself of this.
France is the only country in the EU that uses loans to a large extent.
Germany is demanding 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) are fulfilling their obligations 100% with donations.
In other words, if the vast majority of the European Union spends <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1 to meet its obligations, France gives just 10 cents and understands a comparable bet.
Beautiful hokuspokus!
All in all, France is operating in its fast-start financing with a double blunder: on the one hand with a further development of the action over time and on the other with the reality of financial commitment.
France manages to make it believe that it has spent 420 million "new and additional" millions in accordance with its promises, saving 36.1 million euros.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (since it seems that it was Bercy who carried out the arbitration) could have a double negative effect; once inside the EU (why do the other Member States continue with the donation, if it is enough to borrow?) and then in the negotiations, since the developing countries do not let it go completely.
The chapter on early funding is just a small question for a relatively short period of time compared to the totality of discussions on the climate.
But it could be the drop too much in the immense machinery of the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that this will not be the case.
Anyway, it is essential to learn his lesson from this first year of early funding.
First of all, France could announce a change in its method of recording for the years 2011 and 2012, in the spirit of respect for its obligations and of balancing justice with the other countries of the European Union.
Above all, however, France could bring forward discussions on the subject of long-term financing (another, crucial and currently debated topic): one does not escape the question of "accountability" or the way in which its loans are recorded.
France could change its position to be as progressive on the issues as it is on other things.
The hope is therefore based on the new Minister of the Environment Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprising announcement about France’s fast-start and its vision of “accountability” as well as the use of loans would naturally raise the international confidence base necessary for further discussions.
Alarm - Pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old child takes in 81 different chemical substances over day, according to a study published this Wednesday by the Association of Generations Futures (former movement to protect the rights and respect of future generations).
The association, which explains that its results "in view of the small number of analyzed samples do not represent a statistically significant value, but represent the illustrative nature of the treated problem", had, between July and September, the usual food consumed within four, from an approximately ten-year-old child to meals plus a snack in the supermarkets in Paris.
These typical meals – including the official recommendations of five fresh fruit and vegetables, three dairy products, and 1.5 liters of water per day – have been studied as well as in-house workshops looking for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals, and other pollutants.
The plate balance is staggering: 81 chemical substances, including 42 classified as potentially or probably carcinogenic and five classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances with endocrine disruptors, according to studies by several institutions such as the International Cancer Research Center.
"Even if, in the approximate totality of the cases, the legal limits for each chemical substance individually ingested are not exceeded, it is well deduced from this survey that the reality in which the consumer may be exposed to cancer-causing substances or substances with endocrine disrupting factor," he notes.
Already at breakfast, the butter and milk tea alone already contain more than ten of the potentially carcinogenic residues and three proven to be carcinogens, as well as more than twenty residues that can affect the hormone system.
The apple imported from Brazil, intended as an intermediate meal for the study, shows traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to the green beans from Kenya, including lunch, where the study found traces of an insecticide strictly banned in the EU.
In addition, even the baguette and chewing gum of pesticides and other chemical substances were spiked with the hacksteak, the tuna from the can.
In the case of tap water, the analyses have revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon steak with 34 identified chemical residues was the "richest", and even the plastic plate used to heat the meal in the microwave was not unaffected.
The final risk of this “pollutant cocktail” to consumers “is likely to be underestimated,” the study said.
The Alliance Europe Ecology-Les Verts (EE-LV) has, in turn, proposed "in view of the urgency of the situation" to introduce a moratorium on the use of pesticides to stop the "increase in civilizational diseases".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) had identified the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruits and vegetables that are consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
